<subsection xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"><title> Selecting <m>y_p</m> Forms, Part 1 </title>
		
	<p>
		At this point, if we are given the nonhomogeneous differential equation, 
		<me>
			a_n y^{(n)} + \cdots + a_2 y'' + a_1 y' + a_0 y = f(x)
		</me>,
		we know its general solution has a homogeneous part, found by solving
		<me>
			a_n y^{(n)} + \cdots + a_2 y'' + a_1 y' + a_0 y = 0
		</me>
		and a particular part that is expected to give us the <m>f(x)</m> term on the right-hand side of the equation. The aim of this section is to introduce a strategy for predicting the form of the particular solution based on the form of <m>f(x)</m>. 
	</p>

	<p>
		When <m>f(x)</m> is a polynomial, exponential, sine, cosine, or a combination of these functions, we can safely assume that form of the particular solution should resemble the form of <m>f(x)</m>. That is, if <m>f(x)</m> is a polynomial, then <m>y_p</m> should also be a polynomial. If <m>f(x)</m> is an exponential, then <m>y_p</m> should also be an exponential, and so on. You can use <xref ref="yp-table"/> as a guide for selecting <m>y_p</m>.
	</p>

	<table xml:id="yp-table">
		<title>Selecting <m>y_p</m> given <m>f(x)</m>.
			<fn>The same pattern extends to polynomials of degree higher than 3.</fn>
			Assume <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m> are constants.
		</title>
		<tabular top="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
			<col halign="center" right="medium"/>
			<col halign="center"/>
			<row bottom="medium">
				<cell> <m>f(x)</m> - Type					</cell>
				<cell> <m>y_p</m> - Form					</cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell> constant 						</cell>
				<cell> <m>A</m> 						</cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell> deg 1 polynomial				</cell>
				<cell> <m>Ax+B</m>						</cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell> deg 2 polynomial				</cell>
				<cell> <m>Ax^2+Bx+C</m>					</cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell> deg 3 polynomial				</cell>
				<cell> <m>Ax^3+Bx^2+Cx+D</m>			</cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell> exponential, <m>\ e^{\alpha x}</m>		</cell>
				<cell> <m>A e^{\alpha x}</m>					</cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell> sine, <m>\ \sin(\beta x)</m>			</cell>
				<cell> <m>A \sin(\beta x) + B \cos(\beta x)</m>	</cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell> cosine, <m>\ \cos(\beta x)</m>		</cell>
				<cell> <m>A \sin(\beta x) + B \cos(\beta x)</m>	</cell>
			</row>
			<row bottom="medium">
				<cell> sine + cosine, <m>\ \sin(\beta x) + \cos(\beta x)</m>		</cell>
				<cell> <m>A \sin(\beta x) + B \cos(\beta x)</m>	</cell>
			</row>
		</tabular>
	</table>

